TY  - JOUR
AU  - Fudenberg, Drew
AU  - Levine, David K.
T1  - Maintaining a Reputation when Strategies are Imperfectly Observed
PY  - 1992
Y1  - 1992/07/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297864
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 59
IS  - 3
SP  - 561
EP  - 579
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper studies reputation effects in games with a single long-run player whose choice of stage-game strategy is imperfectly observed by his opponents. We obtain lower and upper bounds on the long-run player's payoff in any Nash equilibrium of the game. If the long-run player's stage-game strategy is statistically identified by the observed outcomes, then for generic payoffs the upper and lower bounds both converge, as the discount factor tends to 1, to the long-run player's Stackelberg payoff, which is the most he could obtain by publicly committing himself to any strategy.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297864
ER  - 



